{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dd7902db-eb6c-49a6-b855-97e4cd0c6595","content":"Here's the scan result for your `my_app/` project:\n\n### Static Dependencies Found\n\n| File | Line | Call | Risk |\n|------|------|------|------|\n| `views.py` | 3 | `datetime.now()` | 🔴 Untestable — returns wall-clock time, impossible to assert against |\n\n### Why it's a problem\n`datetime.now()` is a **hard-coded static call**. In tests, you can't control what time is returned, making it impossible to write deterministic assertions.\n\n### Recommended fix for Django\nUse **Django's `django.utils.timezone.now`** and mock it in tests with [`freezegun`](https://github.com/spulec/freezegun) or `unittest.mock.patch`:\n\n```python\n# views.py — use Django's timezone-aware now\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request):\n    now = timezone.now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\n```python\n# tests.py — freeze time for deterministic tests\nfrom freezegun import freeze_time\n\n@freeze_time(\"2026-04-25 12:00:00\")\ndef test_index(self):\n    response = self.client.get('/')\n    # now you can assert against a known time\n```\n\nYour project is small (1 file), so only **1 call site** needs updating. Want me to apply the fix?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"32651c7d-a798-4d56-a09a-01bd70e28925","outputTokens":344,"requestId":"CFC0:36525B:664407E:7258FB5:69EC2845"},"id":"6d31b792-98be-437d-8323-459be8989868","timestamp":"2026-04-25T02:34:54.490Z","parentId":"7efce4c8-ccd7-4d88-81a5-744bce7afe36"}
